      <span class="hero-tag">Evidence-Based Investigation · Updated July 2026</span>
      <h1>Is OLSP Academy an MLM? An Evidence-Based Investigation of Wayne Crowe's Platform</h1>

      <p><strong>OLSP Academy</strong> is an affiliate-marketing training and commission system created by UK-based marketer Wayne Crowe. It is built around a single tracking link — the "Mega Link" — that members share to earn commissions. But a recurring question follows the platform across every community where it is discussed: <strong>is it an MLM?</strong> Based on FTC regulatory guidance, multiple independent reviews, vendor documentation, and community discussions, our finding is that OLSP Academy shares meaningful structural characteristics with MLMs but does not meet the legal definition of an illegal pyramid scheme. Whether that distinction matters depends on your personal tolerance for MLM-adjacent business models.</p>

      <div class="verdict-box">
        <p><strong>The short answer:</strong> Technically no — OLSP Academy does not meet the FTC's legal definition of an illegal pyramid scheme. Practically, it shares structural characteristics with MLMs, including 2-tier commissions at higher membership levels and a business model where the primary product sold is the membership itself.</p>
        <p><strong>Why you can trust this answer:</strong> This article evaluates OLSP against the FTC's own criteria using evidence from independent reviewers, vendor sales pages, and community discussions — not opinion or affiliation bias.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>What Is the MLM Question About OLSP?</h3>
      <p>OLSP stands for "One Lead System Pixel" according to most sources. It is marketed as a beginner-friendly affiliate system: members get a single link to share, training on how to drive traffic, and commissions when referrals purchase add-ons inside the OLSP ecosystem. The platform has grown since approximately 2020 and its marketing materials claim over 50,000 active students — a figure from OLSP's own affiliate sales page that could not be independently verified.</p>

      <p>The MLM question arises because of how members are compensated. At higher tiers, commissions flow two levels deep — meaning you earn from your direct referrals and from their referrals. Critics point to this structure as MLM-like. Defenders argue the $7 entry fee, the availability of direct sales commissions, and the lack of any purchase requirement distinguish it from MLM models. Both sides have valid points, and the evidence supports a nuanced conclusion.</p>

      <h3>Investigation Methodology</h3>
      <div class="methodology">
        <p><strong>Who wrote this:</strong> This investigation was prepared by an editorial research team that evaluates online business and affiliate marketing programs, with attention to consumer-protection norms around MLM classification and income-opportunity claims.</p>
        <p><strong>How this investigation was built:</strong> We did not purchase, join, or personally test OLSP Academy. This article is based entirely on independent desk research: FTC regulatory guidance, OLSP's own public marketing pages, publicly available independent reviews from multiple sources, community discussions on Reddit and Trustpilot, and general consumer-protection context for affiliate marketing programs. Where a claim could not be independently verified — including most income figures and the official terms of service — we say so explicitly rather than presenting it as fact. Every factual claim in this article is labelled by source reliability.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

