    <section id="accusation">
      <h2>What the Accusation Is</h2>

      <p>The question "Is OLSP an MLM or a scam?" is the single most common question about the platform across online communities. According to independent research that analysed community discussions, this question appears with striking frequency across Reddit, Trustpilot, Quora, and independent review platforms. It is not a fringe concern — it is the dominant question anyone researching OLSP encounters.</p>

      <p>The accusation carries significant emotional weight. Community discussions reveal four distinct fears: wasting money on a program that does not deliver, wasting months of effort with nothing to show, looking foolish by promoting a program that friends and family will recognise as MLM-adjacent, and missing out on a genuine opportunity. Trust and money are at stake simultaneously, and the emotional intensity of the question reflects that.</p>

      <div class="callout warn">
        <strong>Important context:</strong> Community members have raised these accusations, but no legal or regulatory body has made a finding that OLSP Academy operates as an illegal pyramid scheme. The accusation exists in public discussion, not in any court or regulator ruling.
      </div>

      <p>The difficulty for prospective members is that the available information is structurally biased. According to multiple independent reviewers, most positive reviews of OLSP come from members who earn affiliate commissions, while negative reviews may come from people who gave up or never joined. Independent review sites that cover OLSP are split roughly evenly, with the negative side specifically noting that most positive reviews come from members who are themselves promoting OLSP through their own referral links. Trustpilot shows a 4.2/5 TrustScore from 209 reviews, though OLSP does not actively solicit reviews and the volume is low relative to its claimed member base of 50,000+.</p>

      <p>This article exists to fill the gap that no neutral, evidence-based assessment currently occupies. We provide the legal framework from the FTC, factual evidence about OLSP's structure from independent sources, and a decision framework you can use to make your own call.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="legal-definition">
      <h2>The Legal Definition of MLM</h2>

      <p>Before evaluating OLSP, we need a clear, authoritative definition of what an MLM is — and more importantly, what distinguishes a legal MLM from an illegal pyramid scheme under US federal law.</p>

      <h3>The FTC Framework</h3>
      <p>The US Federal Trade Commission defines an illegal pyramid scheme as an enterprise "characterised by the payment by participants of money to the company in return for which they receive (1) the right to sell a product and (2) the right to receive in return for recruiting other participants into the program rewards which are unrelated to the sale of the product to ultimate users." This definition comes from the 1975 <em>Koscot</em> court decision and remains the canonical legal standard, according to the FTC's own Business Guidance concerning multi-level marketing.</p>

      <p>The FTC explicitly states there is no percentage-based safe harbour. There is no rule that says "if commissions from recruitment stay below X%, it is legal." Instead, the FTC evaluates the entire business model on a case-by-case basis, examining multiple factors holistically.</p>

      <h3>Key FTC Evaluation Criteria</h3>
      <p>According to the FTC's Business Guidance, the following factors are examined to distinguish a legal MLM from an illegal pyramid scheme:</p>

      <div class="table-scroll">
      <table>
        <tr><th>Factor</th><th>What the FTC Examines</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Incentive structure</td><td>What behaviour does the compensation plan incentivise — recruitment or product sales?</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Income expectations</td><td>What earnings claims does the marketing create, and are they substantiated?</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Training and messaging</td><td>What are participants taught to prioritise — selling products or recruiting others?</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Entry motivation</td><td>Why do people actually sign up — to earn from sales or to earn from recruitment?</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Actual earnings</td><td>How do participants actually make money in practice, not just in theory?</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Customer base</td><td>Who buys the products — actual external customers or the participants themselves?</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Participant losses</td><td>Do participants experience financial losses, which the FTC notes are "inevitable due to the structure of the pyramid scheme"?</td></tr>
      </table>
      </div>

      <div class="callout info">
        <strong>Key takeaway:</strong> There is no single yes/no test. The FTC evaluates the whole picture. A program can have some MLM-like features without being an illegal pyramid scheme — and it can be a legal MLM while still being a poor fit for many people.
      </div>
    </section>

