          <td><strong>Yes, at higher tiers.</strong> The Team Builders/Community Builders level includes 2-tier commissions — you earn from your referrals and from their referrals. This is the structural characteristic that most closely matches MLM compensation models.</td>
          <td>Multiple independent reviewers; OLSP Team Builders sales page</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Primary product is membership itself</td>
          <td><strong>Partially.</strong> Most commissions are earned by promoting OLSP's own membership tiers and marketing tools. Independent reviewers note the training focuses almost exclusively on selling OLSP products rather than third-party affiliate offers.</td>
          <td>Multiple independent reviewers</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>System growth depends on recruitment</td>
          <td><strong>Partially.</strong> Because the primary product is membership in the system itself, continuous new member acquisition is required to sustain commission flows. This is a structural feature of any program where the product is the program.</td>
          <td>Multiple independent reviewers</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Large upfront entry fee</td>
          <td><strong>No.</strong> The minimum entry is $7, far lower than most MLM entry fees. However, independent reviewers note that the realistic investment for meaningful earning potential is $49–$199/month or more at higher tiers.</td>
          <td>Multiple independent reviewers</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Inventory purchase requirements</td>
          <td><strong>No.</strong> There is no requirement to purchase or hold inventory. Members promote digital products and memberships.</td>
          <td>Multiple independent reviewers</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Earnings claims substantiated</td>
          <td><strong>No.</strong> OLSP does not publish member earnings data. Marketing claims of "$50M+ Student Earnings" and "$3,000–$10,000+ per month" are from OLSP's own marketing materials and could not be independently verified. OLSP Academy does not publish member earnings data — the only available figures are self-reported in community discussions and could not be independently verified.</td>
          <td>OLSP marketing materials (unverified); community discussions</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Training emphasis</td>
          <td><strong>MLM-adjacent.</strong> Training teaches real marketing skills — email marketing, traffic generation, list building — but applies these skills primarily to promoting OLSP's own products. The skills are transferable, but the application context is narrow.</td>
          <td>Multiple independent reviewers</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      </div>

      <h3>The Core Finding</h3>
      <p>Multiple independent reviewers consistently reach the same conclusion: OLSP shares structural characteristics with MLMs but is not a legal pyramid scheme. According to one independent reviewer who provides the most explicit analysis on this point, "OLSP is not technically a multi-level marketing company in the legal sense. It does not require recruitment to participate, income can be generated from direct product sales, and the product catalogue contains real digital tools and training. It does, however, share structural characteristics with MLM."</p>

      <div class="callout warn">
        <strong>The unsatisfying truth:</strong> OLSP is not legally a pyramid scheme, but it operates in the same structural neighbourhood as MLMs. Whether that distinction matters depends on your personal tolerance for MLM-adjacent models — which is precisely what the decision framework in the next section addresses.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="unsatisfying-answer">
      <h2>Why the Answer Is Unsatisfying</h2>

      <p>If you reached this section hoping for a simple yes or no, you are not alone. Community discussions show that most people researching OLSP want a binary answer. The evidence does not support one. Here is why:</p>

      <h3>1. The legal definition is situational, not mechanical</h3>
      <p>The FTC evaluates business models holistically, not by checking boxes. Two programs with identical commission structures could receive different evaluations based on how they train members, what earnings claims they make, and who actually buys their products. There is no definitive checklist for OLSP to pass or fail — only a judgment call based on all available evidence.</p>

      <h3>2. The available information is structurally biased</h3>
      <p>Every source of information about OLSP has a built-in bias. According to independent reviewers and community analysis, positive sources have financial incentive — most write-ups rank for OLSP keywords and carry affiliate links. Negative sources may be uninformed or disgruntled. Trustpilot data shows a 4.2/5 score from 209 reviews, though the platform does not actively solicit reviews and the volume is low relative to its claimed member base of 50,000+, making the sample self-selected rather than statistically representative.</p>

      <h3>3. "Legally acceptable" and "personally acceptable" are different questions</h3>
      <p>A program can be fully legal under FTC guidelines and still be a bad fit for you personally. The question you are really asking may not be "Is OLSP legally an MLM?" but rather "Will I be comfortable building my business in a system that shares MLM characteristics?" Those are different questions, and only you can answer the second one.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="decision-framework">
      <h2>Your Decision Framework</h2>

      <p>Instead of offering a yes/no answer that the evidence cannot support, here are three questions to ask yourself. Your answers will tell you whether OLSP's structure is acceptable for your situation.</p>

      <div class="callout info">
        <strong>Are you comfortable earning primarily from promoting the platform's own membership?</strong> If your goal is to promote a wide range of third-party products as an affiliate, OLSP may feel constraining. If you are comfortable with the primary product being the membership itself — as is the case with many training platforms — the structure may not bother you.
      </div>

      <div class="callout info">
        <strong>Does a 2-tier commission structure bother you?</strong> The Team Builders tier pays commissions two levels deep. This is the characteristic that most closely resembles MLM compensation. If earning from your referrals' referrals makes you uncomfortable, consider staying at lower tiers or choosing a different platform. If you see it as a legitimate way to earn from team building, it may not be an issue.
      </div>

      <div class="callout info">
        <strong>Can you generate your own traffic without relying on built-in systems?</strong> OLSP provides training and tools, but according to multiple independent reviewers, members still need to generate their own traffic. Community discussions document members who joined expecting automated traffic and earned nothing. If you have traffic generation skills or are willing to learn them, the system can work. If you expect built-in traffic, you may be disappointed.
      </div>

      <p>If you answered "no" to two or more of these questions, OLSP's structure may not be a comfortable fit — regardless of whether it meets the legal definition of an MLM. If you answered "yes" to all three, the structural questions are likely not a barrier for you.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="conclusion">
      <h2>Conclusion: Your Call</h2>

      <p>OLSP Academy occupies a grey area. It is not an illegal pyramid scheme by the FTC's definition — no regulatory body has made such a finding, and the evidence does not support that conclusion. Direct sales are always possible, the $7 entry barrier is low, and real digital products are sold. It would not be accurate or fair to label OLSP a pyramid scheme.</p>

      <p>But OLSP also shares meaningful structural characteristics with MLMs. The 2-tier commission system at the Team Builders level, the focus on selling the membership itself, and the system's dependence on continuous recruitment create an environment that many people experience as MLM-adjacent. Community discussions make it clear: the MLM feel is real for many members, even if the legal definition is not satisfied.</p>

      <p>This article has presented the evidence, the legal framework, and the practical realities. We have not taken a side because the evidence does not support a single binary conclusion. What the evidence does support is your right to make an informed decision based on your own values, goals, and tolerance for MLM-adjacent structures.</p>

      <p>If you decide OLSP is worth exploring, the $7 Mega Link entry is low-risk enough to evaluate first-hand. If you decide it is not the right fit, that is a valid conclusion — and you now have the evidence to explain why.</p>

      <p>Wayne Crowe is a publicly identifiable UK-based affiliate marketer who, according to his LinkedIn profile and multiple independent reviews, has been teaching digital marketing since 2011 and founded the OLSP System around 2020. Multiple independent sources confirm he runs a live training program with consistent attendance and has built a platform with real digital products — regardless of whether one agrees with the commission structure.</p>

