    <section id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Is OLSP Academy an MLM?</summary>
        <p>OLSP Academy shares structural characteristics with MLMs — including 2-tier commissions at higher membership levels and a business model where the primary product sold is the membership itself — but it does not meet the FTC's legal definition of an illegal pyramid scheme. The distinction matters legally but may not matter practically for someone deciding whether the model is comfortable for them.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is OLSP Academy a pyramid scheme?</summary>
        <p>No legal or regulatory body has found OLSP Academy to be a pyramid scheme. The FTC defines an illegal pyramid scheme by the relationship between recruitment rewards and product sales — and OLSP offers direct sales commissions from a $7 entry point without requiring recruitment. However, the 2-tier commission structure and the focus on selling the membership itself create substantial structural overlap with MLM models.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Do I have to recruit people to make money at OLSP?</summary>
        <p>No. According to multiple independent reviewers, members can earn commissions from direct sales of the Mega Link and other OLSP products without recruiting anyone. The 100% commission on Mega Link front-end sales is available at all levels. Higher tiers add 2-tier commissions as an additional earning method, but direct sales remain an option at every level.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How is OLSP different from other affiliate training platforms?</summary>
        <p>Like OLSP, platforms such as Wealthy Affiliate and Legendary Marketer offer tiered memberships and affiliate programs for their own products. The key differences are structural: Wealthy Affiliate does not offer multi-tier commissions, while Legendary Marketer has a compensation plan that some critics also compare to MLM. Each platform should be evaluated individually against FTC criteria.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can I trust positive reviews of OLSP Academy?</summary>
        <p>Most positive reviews of OLSP come from members who earn affiliate commissions — including many of the independent review sites that rank for OLSP-related searches. This does not automatically make them wrong, but it means the reviewer has a financial interest in your decision. Cross-reference claims across multiple sources, look for reviewers who acknowledge their affiliate relationship, and prioritise sources that provide specific, verifiable data over general enthusiasm.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What percentage of OLSP members actually earn money?</summary>
        <p>OLSP Academy does not publish member earnings data. The only available earnings figures are self-reported in community discussions and could not be independently verified. Industry-wide, studies find that approximately 99% of MLM participants lose money across 350 US MLMs, but this is a general industry statistic, not specific to OLSP.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

